WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Hello everyone, yes, I'm Tyler Morgan-Wall.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:10.000
I'm the developer of RayShader and the Rayverse, a collection of packages for 3D data visualization and mapping,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
and a researcher at the Institute for Defense Analyses in Alexandria, Virginia,

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:20.000
and today I'm going to be talking to you about Quarto, AI, and the Art of Getting Your Life Back.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
So late last year, I had done something really cool, and I wanted to share it with the world.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.000
I had created an R package that allowed you to transform 2D geospatial data of building footprints into 3D buildings

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.000
and generate entire cities in a matter of minutes.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.000
But getting the coding finished was just the beginning.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Without explaining the value of what I had done in terms of solving actual problems,

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
the chance that someone would both come across my work and come to the conclusion on their own

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
that it was worth their time was next to none.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
So how was I going to get it out there?

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Well, I decided to write a blog post about it.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Even if I wrote great documentation in the package itself,

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:03.000
documentation focuses on the how to use the package and not the why to use the package.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.000
With a blog post, you can tell your project's origin story,

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.000
what problem or idea brought it into being,

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
and the trials and tribulations you encountered on your journey to solve those problems.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Additionally, with a blog post, you control the medium.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
You can add as many high-quality images and videos or make it as long as you want,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
and there is absolutely no chance that your blog will be purchased by Elon Musk.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Now, I've run my own blog since 2016,

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
and having a place to feature my own long-form content has been a great boon for my professional life.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
However, when I was first getting started and trying to spin up my blog,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.000
it immediately became apparent that actually running a blog is awful.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Having to deal with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.000
on top of the hard technical work I was already doing with R, no thank you.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:54.000
So after a bit of research, I decided to run my blog on WordPress.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Now, if you don't know, WordPress powers over 40% of all websites on the Internet.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
It's so popular because it's super easy to theme, customize, and publish content

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.000
without any technical background.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
So it seemed like the obvious choice for somebody who wanted to spend as little time

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
on the actual act of running a blog as possible.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
But appearances can be deceiving.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
The downside to WordPress' ubiquity is it's constantly being probed by hackers,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.000
so security updates are essential and unrelentingly frequent.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And at the time I went to publish this post on 3DCities,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
I discovered I couldn't install these security updates without updating my Linux distribution,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
which I couldn't do because my server didn't have enough space,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
so I'd have to upgrade it, and figuring this out was taking a lot of time,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:44.000
and I wanted to be spending time doing the stuff I actually enjoy doing,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
not server maintenance.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
So I was also, though, dreading the idea of moving away from WordPress

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
because it had such nice facilities for publishing content and customizing

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.000
and adding cool dynamic features to my website.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:01.000
So basically I wanted it all.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
I wanted the easy ability to publish content,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
but I didn't want all of the tedious server maintenance.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:11.000
So enter Quarto.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Quarto builds static sites so there's no constant parade of security updates.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
However, customizing your website is harder because you have to do so manually.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And while in the past that meant having to learn languages like CSS and JavaScript,

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:29.000
the development of large language models, which henceforth are referred to as AI,

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
has greatly lowered this barrier to entry.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
So here's what you should expect to take away from this talk.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
First, I'm going to tell you the one weird trick

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
I use to convert an existing blog to Quarto.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Second, I'm going to tell you how you can automate your website's deployment

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
by using something called Quarto render hooks.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And then finally, I'm going to tell you how you can customize

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:56.000
and add cool dynamic features to your Quarto website using AI.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
So to begin, let's say you have an existing website, Quarto or otherwise,

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.000
and after this talk you decide that you're going to switch to Quarto.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
How would you go about doing that?

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Doing the absolute bare minimum amount of work.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So to give you some context, I originally wrote all of my blog posts in R Markdown,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
knitted them to HTML, and then just copied that raw HTML into my WordPress editor.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.000
So I could have gone back to the RMD files and manually converted them to QMD files,

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.000
but that would have been a lot of time and effort, and again, I did not want to do that.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So here is an example of one of my old blog posts on WordPress,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
and to illustrate the trick I'm going to use, let's compare this.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Note that the content is actually not important,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:45.000
but just that it is raw HTML pasted into the WordPress editor.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:51.000
So for the trick, let's look at one of my new posts in the QMD format for my new website,

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:59.000
which, if you look closely, is the exact same content.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And that is the trick.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:07.000
You can just copy and paste your old blog post's HTML directly into a QMD file.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:13.000
When you render your Quarto website, that text will render as HTML, not text.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:19.000
You can also put it in a raw HTML block if you'd like, but you don't have to.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:23.000
The only work I had to do in this transition was to write a Quarto header for each post.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Now, these are places where you specify the title and authors and date,

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:30.000
but you could also add shared content to each post.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So on my old website, I had custom JavaScript and style sheets added to each post

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
via a global customization option in WordPress,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
and I was able to add these to the old posts on my new site via this include in header,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
include after body, and CSS fields.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Additionally, you can specify a featured image for each post,

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:54.000
which here you might note is actually still pointing to a WordPress-specific media directory, wp-content.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.000
In order to complete the full transition, all I did was copy this directory

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:05.000
and all of its subdirectories to my new site, and that is how I transition my site to Quarto.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:09.000
So let's look and compare one of my old blog posts and the new one.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.000
So here is an example of one of my old blog posts on my old website,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:16.000
and here is the new version of that.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:20.000
Different style, but note that all of the content is rendered perfectly,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
and it only required writing a few Quarto headers.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
And because this trick used just HTML, this could potentially apply to other blogging frameworks as well,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:35.000
although particularly in this case, if you had an RMD file, that's what makes this, I think, so seamless.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Additionally, the only caveat is that if you have hard-coded layout elements

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
that depend on the specific design of a page or things like dynamic content such as WordPress shortcodes,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
those would have to be handled manually, but I had very few of those,

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.000
so this was basically the whole process.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
However, having converted my website to Quarto,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:58.000
I now face the next issue, which is actually getting it online.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
Because in WordPress, I could just press the button Publish Post,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
and my content was online.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
I wanted the equivalent of that Publish Post button in RStudio,

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:14.000
and for me, that meant never having to touch a terminal and being able to do this entirely from my Quarto project.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So how could I do that?

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.000
With Quarto Render Hooks.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Quarto Render Hooks are a neat and powerful feature

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
that allow you to inject your own scripts into the Quarto rendering pipeline.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
You can specify them in your project-level Quarto file like this.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
These can be arbitrary shell commands, Lua, Python, and R scripts.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.000
So here, I specified a pre-render hook that just prints a fun message,

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
as well as a post-render hook that does some actual work.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
For example, in my website, I store my media into non-standard directories,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.000
posts and videos located within my posts directory.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And when I render my Quarto website, these are not automatically copied over.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:58.000
So all the first two post-render hooks do is copy those over to my site directory.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:05.000
I then call an R script called transferSite that does exactly what it sounds like.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
But note the one little argument at the end of this script.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
What exactly is that doing?

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
So let's dive into the script and see.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:20.000
That little string is just effectively the toggle button to upload my site.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:25.000
When I don't want to upload my site and just work locally,

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
I just change this string to anything else.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:30.000
And in R, you can use this command args function

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:34.000
to inspect what extra arguments are passed R when you called R.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
And when I change this to something else,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.000
this just skips the uploading process and just renders locally.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
I also then remind future me how to turn uploading back on

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.000
because that is just basic programming self-care.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Now, here's the meat of the automation.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.000
So what I do here is just specify my local directories, my remote directories.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.000
And then I call this rsync utility via a system call,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
which then uploads the site. And that's it.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
Since I put this together, I haven't had to touch a terminal.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
I've been able to publish multiple blog posts and edit my site

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:15.000
without ever thinking about any technical steps in between.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:19.000
And even though I had never used rsync before,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.000
I learned to use it very quickly by using AI.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:32.000
So AI is a great tool for learning new and well-established utilities

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:37.000
such as rsync or popular languages like CSS and JavaScript.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
And that is what brings me to the last part of my talk,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
customizing your website with AI.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:48.000
While transitioning from a server-generated framework like WordPress

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
to a static framework like Querto

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
brings many performance and maintenance improvements,

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
it does also limit some of the cool dynamic features of your website.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
And by moving from a massively popular tool like WordPress

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
to a relatively new tool like Querto,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
you lose a lot of the great community resources and tools

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:10.000
that have been developed to help you go through that process.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:15.000
So the development of AI, however, has vastly evened this playing field.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:19.000
The current batch of AI tools are in large part trained on web-based data,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
and we are trying to build a website.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:25.000
So while AI is not good at things necessarily like data science

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
or being really good at R or critical thinking or basic mathematics,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
it is pretty good at asking you things like,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
hey, generate the CSS for me to make my submit form button

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
sashay across the page when I press it.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
So let's do that.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
Not dancing buttons, but let's add some nice decorative 3D effects

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
to our Querto main page.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.000
So here are the Querto postcards

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
for each one of my blog posts on my old website.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I wanted some sort of subtle 3D effect like that on my Querto main page.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
So let's look and see what we're starting with in Querto.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So this is the default Querto postcards,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
completely static with a white background.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:08.000
They're fine.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
I wanted to write some CSS to add some subtle animations

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
and that sort of 3D pop-out effect when a reader mouths over the card.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.000
To do so, I iterated back and forth with ChatGPT,

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:25.000
adding the generated CSS to my Querto style.css file

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
and then provided feedback with each iteration,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:31.000
which honed in on the effect I was after.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:39.000
We made small adjustments to the existing CSS

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
to get closer to what I wanted.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And note that nowhere in my prompts was I using technical language

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
specific to CSS to request what I wanted.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
I was using plain descriptive language,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
like tilting a piece of brushed metal

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
rather than asking for specific CSS features or classes.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And that's one of the really strengths of AI

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
is that it's very good at translating your plain language request

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.000
into specific features and functionality in these languages.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
And even if it doesn't get the implementation exactly right,

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
it will often get you about 90% there

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
just by pointing out the features relevant to your response.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
And the risk of AI giving you the wrong answer,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
which is always present,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.000
can be mitigated if you have the ability to quickly check for correctness,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.000
which you can do here simply by rendering the page.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So after 10 minutes, back and forth the chat GPT,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
this was the final result,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
a nice little 3D effect on my Quarto landing page

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
made entirely with AI.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:42.000
However, this was a relatively easy ask of AI

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
since what I was asking for was a relatively common

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
and simple decorative effect.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:50.000
How could the AI handle something with user interactivity

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
and imposed design constraints?

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
So that brings me to the second effect I wanted AI to assist me on,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
which is an image carousel.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
So on my old website, I had an image carousel

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
that faded through the seven most recent posts

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
at the top of the main page,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:09.000
as well as showed the title

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
and put an image selector at the bottom

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
that allowed you to select and go between the images.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
So in WordPress, this was actually generated dynamically

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
every single time you went to the website.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
The page would query the server,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
it would generate the most recent posts,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
and then some JavaScript would transform that

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
into an image carousel.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
So how could I recreate this in Quarto?

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
To do so, I would need two elements.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
First, I would need a way to query the most recent posts

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
when I rendered the website,

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
and then I would need some JavaScript to transform it

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
into an image carousel.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
And thankfully, I didn't have to use AI for the first portion

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
because I took a workshop in Quarto

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
at this very conference two years ago

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
that gave me the solution for what I needed,

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
which is document listings.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Document listings allow you to generate a feed

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
of categorized and recent posts and add them to any Quarto page.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
And so here, the Quarto main page

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
consists of a main listing of all posts,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
but you can add as many additional listings as you want.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
So here I added an additional listing above the first

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
of the most recent seven posts.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Now I need a way to transform these

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
into the image carousel.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
So the first thing we can do entirely in Quarto

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
is just get them to the right size.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
And I adjust it to take the full width of the main page,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
of the main content area on the main page,

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
and then I adjust the image height

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
via the image height argument,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:33.000
and then to our desired final image height for our carousel.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And then I just need to write some JavaScript

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.000
to transform those into an image carousel.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.000
So that was an animated mock-up of what I was attempting to do

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
with each post card.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
So this process was a bit more involved

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
than the CSS one, unsurprisingly,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
so I'm not going to go through the full series of prompts.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
But what I will do is share with you

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
four useful prompting strategies

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
that I developed as I was working with AI.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
So the first, and unsurprisingly, I think,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
is it's very good to give the AI

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
the exact source code you want it to manipulate

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
so that it has access to the structure

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
and classes in your page.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
So here I just copied and pasted the listing HTML

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
directly into my prompt

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
and then asked it to transform it into an image carousel.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
Second, as you iterate,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:27.000
it can often be good to constantly remind the AI

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.000
what the current status of your script looks like.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
So even if it just generated for you a few prompts prior,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
AIs can lose focus over time due to their limited context window,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and I found if I didn't constantly remind the AI

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
what the current status was, it would kind of forget

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
and make really bad mistakes.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
And by providing it that current version,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
it actually ended up much more likely

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
to give me a relevant response.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Third, if you have visual details

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.000
you want the AI to adjust,

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
it can often be helpful to provide a screenshot of the issue

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
as well as the description of it with your prompt.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
So here I had successfully transformed

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
the post title into a semi-transparent gray overlay

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
on the image.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
However, it had a very small few pixel gap

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
at the bottom that I wanted removed.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
So I provided the screenshot and a description of the image,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
or a description of the problem,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
and the AI was able to issue a fix.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.000
And then finally, sometimes the AI can seemingly get stuck

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
and be unable to solve a problem solely by prompting.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
So, for example, I managed to get the AI

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
to come up with an almost complete implementation

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
of my image carousel, but there were one or two issues

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
that it could not seem to solve just solely by prompting.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
So at that point, I just started asking the AI

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
to explain the purpose of a specific snippet of code,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
and then once I understood what the code was doing,

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
I just went in and solved the problem myself.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:56.000
So AI can be middling at best when actually writing code,

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
but I found that it's actually very good

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
and very consistent at explaining the purpose

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:04.000
of specific snippets of code.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:08.000
So combining the breadth of AI's knowledge

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.000
with your far superior problem-solving skills

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
can really supercharge your development speed.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
And while I didn't escape entirely unscathed

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
from boring and tedious front-end work,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.000
the final result was pretty much exactly what I had in mind.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
In fact, I liked it a little better

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
than the original WordPress version

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.000
because this one actually rotated between images

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
rather than just faded, as you'd think something

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
called an image carousel would.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:40.000
So in the end, my site was faster, better,

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
easier to maintain.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
I guess the moral of the story is with Quarto,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
you can have it all.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:51.000
So as a takeaway, Quarto can render pre-existing HTML

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
pasted into a QMD file.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
A very simple but powerful fact.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
Second, you can use Quarto render hooks

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
to automate much of the tedious parts

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:02.000
of website deployment and publishing away,

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
and these can be written in R,

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
and you can control them entirely

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
via your project-level Quarto file.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.000
And then finally, while AI can write code for you,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
it's often much more useful as a learning resource

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
when working with unfamiliar tools.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:21.000
So using AI can help you focus on doing the things

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
you actually like and save time

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
so you can do those things that you love.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
So thank you.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
Thank you.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
We have just a minute for a question.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
There we go.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
Would you recommend integrating the Rsync bit

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
into a workflow for rendering and uploading

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
a Quarto website deposit connect?

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:51.000
I don't know if you know.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
I can't speak to that.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
Then we'll ask the other one.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.000
You kind of answered this a little bit,

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:58.000
but what are your thoughts on just, like,

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
language-specific LLMs, so, like,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.000
in particular for assistance with, like, R code?

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.000
Yeah, I found it to be, I mean,

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
I've used the various forms of chat,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
GPT-4.0, the latest version.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
I found it to be, you know,

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:13.000
it's best of the things I've seen a lot,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:17.000
and in particular, there's far less R code out there

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:18.000
than there is at other code,

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
and particularly a lot of the use cases for R code

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
is very data science-focused, where there's actual,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
like, you know, important things on the line,

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.000
and I found it to make really egregious mistakes

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
in basic statistics to the point where I would never,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:32.000
unless you have that, again,

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:34.000
that ability to quickly check for correctness

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:35.000
in a way that you're 100% sure

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
it's giving you the right result,

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:40.000
I don't trust it further than I can check,

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:42.000
so that's my opinion on that.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
Great. Thank you, Tyler.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:45.000
Thank you.

